      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>How much homework should a teacher assign (front page, Oct. 10)? The answer is easy: the amount that can be reviewed in class the next day within 10 minutes for each subject.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>How much homework should a teacher assign (front page, Oct. 10)? The answer is easy: the amount that can be reviewed in class the next day within 10 minutes for each subject.</p>
        <p>Homework that is not reviewed in class soon after it is assigned is of little value. Homework should represent a challenge or application of classwork, both of which need reinforcement by the teacher. If the teacher cannot find the time, students should not be required to give the time.</p>
        <p>HELEN SULTANIK  Brooklyn, Oct. 11, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is the science coordinator for the Board of Jewish Education.</p>
      </block>
